This is of course, ideal, but customer journeys can be way complex. 

The point is identifying the pillars of your growth ecosystem and building it to support growth is key instead of just focusing on one aspect to drive it.

They're now mildly active, you now engage them with offers/discounts/community activities (value-led) ⇾ they're now very active. 

Finally, after engaging with your emails, activities, notifications, they understand your product in depth and convert for whatever you're selling.

Example: A user that lands on your blog via SEO, knows you exist.

Forgets about it, you retarget them with an ad, they get curious. Still don't download the app.

Days later, they see a social media post on your page that went viral on your page, get curious, download the app.

Growth isn't just about customer acquisition, it's about creating a sustainable ecosystem that creates a pull to continuously drive your north star metric from as many directions you can build. 

It's a mindset, a process, a commitment to constant experimentation & optimisation.

5.2. Realised engineering isn’t for me post 2 years but wanted to continue with my interest in CS & Entrepreneurship.

Joined @AshokaUniv and graduated in 2022! Worked alongside all these 5 years in college and here I am :D

5.1. Followed — you make ‘you’ and not the building you study in. 

Ended up in a tier 3 engineering college, made the most of my time there; got invited to many international conferences.

5. I decided to take the road not taken with my studies. Most of the folks thought I’m making a huge mistake but I always prioritised my health and sleep over tuitions/coachings in my 12th. 

Computer Science was always my first choice but never chased entrances or IITs.

4. I’m a big foodie (don’t know where all of it goes but yes), and a traveler (traveled solo to 6+ countries on my own).

These are the only two places where I empty my bank account. Always have loved meeting new folks, and keep meeting them in whichever city I am!

3.1. I source my strength, resilience and sportsmanship from sports. 

There was a point in life when I used to train for 12 hours a day under my coach for Basketball and those were the days that taught me most of these values.

3. Sports has been a huge part of building who I am, from playing states - badminton, zonals - chess to being a professional horse rider, skater, and nationals - basketball, I’ve loved playing each and every sport.
